events.description: Legions loyal to the Roman Senate, commanded by Gaius Pansa, defeat the forces of Mark Antony in the Battle of Forum Gallorum.

events.description: Otto II, Co-Emperor of the Holy Roman Empire, marries Byzantine princess Theophanu. She is crowned empress by Pope John XIII in Rome the same day.

events.description: Tokhtamysh–Timur war: At the Battle of the Terek River, Timur defeats the army of the Golden Horde, beginning the khanate's permanent military decline.
events.html: • 1395 – Tokhtamysh–Timur war: At the Battle of the Terek River, Timur defeats the army of the Golden Horde, beginning the khanate's permanent military decline.[5]

events.description: In England, the Yorkists under Edward IV defeat the Lancastrians under the Earl of Warwick at the Battle of Barnet; the Earl is killed and Edward resumes the throne.
events.html: • 1471 – In England, the Yorkists under Edward IV defeat the Lancastrians under the Earl of Warwick at the Battle of Barnet; the Earl is killed and Edward resumes the throne.[6]

events.description: A celestial phenomenon is reported over Nuremberg, described as an aerial battle.
events.html: • 1561 – A celestial phenomenon is reported over Nuremberg, described as an aerial battle.[7]

events.description: Thirty Years' War: Forces of the Holy Roman Empire and Electorate of Saxony are defeated by the Swedes at the Battle of Chemnitz, ending the military effectiveness of the Saxon army for the rest of the war and allowing the Swedes to advance into Bohemia.
events.html: • 1639 – Thirty Years' War: Forces of the Holy Roman Empire and Electorate of Saxony are defeated by the Swedes at the Battle of Chemnitz, ending the military effectiveness of the Saxon army for the rest of the war and allowing the Swedes to advance into Bohemia.[8]

events.description: The Society for the Relief of Free Negroes Unlawfully Held in Bondage, the first abolition society in North America, is organized in Philadelphia by Benjamin Franklin and Benjamin Rush.
events.html: • 1775 – The Society for the Relief of Free Negroes Unlawfully Held in Bondage, the first abolition society in North America, is organized in Philadelphia by Benjamin Franklin and Benjamin Rush.[9]

events.description: The French troops led by Léger-Félicité Sonthonax defeat the slaves settlers in the Siege of Port-au-Prince.
events.html: • 1793 – The French troops led by Léger-Félicité Sonthonax defeat the slaves settlers in the Siege of Port-au-Prince.[10]

events.description: Bussa, a slave in British-ruled Barbados, leads a slave rebellion, for which he is remembered as the country's first national hero.
events.html: • 1816 – Bussa, a slave in British-ruled Barbados, leads a slave rebellion, for which he is remembered as the country's first national hero.[11]

events.description: Hungary declares itself independent of Austria with Lajos Kossuth as its leader.
events.html: • 1849 – Hungary declares itself independent of Austria with Lajos Kossuth as its leader.[12]

events.description: The 1858 Christiania fire severely destroys several city blocks near Stortorvet in Christiania, Norway, and about 1,000 people lose their homes.
events.html: • 1858 – The 1858 Christiania fire severely destroys several city blocks near Stortorvet in Christiania, Norway, and about 1,000 people lose their homes.[13]

events.description: U.S. President Abraham Lincoln is shot in Ford's Theatre by John Wilkes Booth; Lincoln dies the following day.
events.html: • 1865 – U.S. President Abraham Lincoln is shot in Ford's Theatre by John Wilkes Booth; Lincoln dies the following day.[14]

events.description: William H. Seward, the U.S. Secretary of State, and his family are attacked at home by Lewis Powell.
events.html: • 1865 – William H. Seward, the U.S. Secretary of State, and his family are attacked at home by Lewis Powell.[15]

events.description: The Four Dead in Five Seconds Gunfight occurs in El Paso, Texas.
events.html: • 1881 – The Four Dead in Five Seconds Gunfight occurs in El Paso, Texas.[16]

events.description: The Pan-American Union is founded by the First International Conference of American States in Washington, D.C.
events.html: • 1890 – The Pan-American Union is founded by the First International Conference of American States in Washington, D.C.[17]

events.description: The first ever commercial motion picture house opens in New York City, United States. It uses ten Kinetoscopes, devices for peep-show viewing of films.
events.html: • 1894 – The first ever commercial motion picture house opens in New York City, United States. It uses ten Kinetoscopes, devices for peep-show viewing of films.[18]

events.description: The 1895 Ljubljana earthquake, both the most and last destructive earthquake in the area, occurs.
events.html: • 1895 – The 1895 Ljubljana earthquake, both the most and last destructive earthquake in the area, occurs.[19]

events.description: The world's fair Exposition Universelle opens in Paris.
events.html: • 1900 – The world's fair Exposition Universelle opens in Paris.[20]

events.description: The first meeting of the Azusa Street Revival, which will launch Pentecostalism as a worldwide movement, is held in Los Angeles.
events.html: • 1906 – The first meeting of the Azusa Street Revival, which will launch Pentecostalism as a worldwide movement, is held in Los Angeles.

events.description: Hauser Dam, a steel dam on the Missouri River in Montana, fails, sending a surge of water 25 to 30 feet (7.6 to 9.1 m) high downstream.
events.html: • 1908 – Hauser Dam, a steel dam on the Missouri River in Montana, fails, sending a surge of water 25 to 30 feet (7.6 to 9.1 m) high downstream.

events.description: Muslims in the Ottoman Empire begin a massacre of Armenians in Adana.
events.html: • 1909 – Muslims in the Ottoman Empire begin a massacre of Armenians in Adana.[21]

events.description: The British passenger liner RMS Titanic hits an iceberg in the North Atlantic and begins to sink.
events.html: • 1912 – The British passenger liner RMS Titanic hits an iceberg in the North Atlantic and begins to sink.

events.description: The Bremen, a German Junkers W 33 type aircraft, reaches Greenly Island, Canada, completing the first successful transatlantic aeroplane flight from east to west.
events.html: • 1928 – The Bremen, a German Junkers W 33 type aircraft, reaches Greenly Island, Canada, completing the first successful transatlantic aeroplane flight from east to west.

events.description: The inaugural Monaco Grand Prix takes place in the Principality of Monaco. William Grover-Williams wins driving a Bugatti Type 35.
events.html: • 1929 – The inaugural Monaco Grand Prix takes place in the Principality of Monaco. William Grover-Williams wins driving a Bugatti Type 35.[22]

events.description: The Second Spanish Republic is proclaimed and king Alfonso XIII goes to exile. Meanwhile, in Barcelona, Francesc Macià proclaims the Catalan Republic.
events.html: • 1931 – The Second Spanish Republic is proclaimed and king Alfonso XIII goes to exile. Meanwhile, in Barcelona, Francesc Macià proclaims the Catalan Republic.[23]

events.description: The Black Sunday dust storm, considered one of the worst storms of the Dust Bowl, sweeps across the Oklahoma and Texas panhandles and neighboring areas.
events.html: • 1935 – The Black Sunday dust storm, considered one of the worst storms of the Dust Bowl, sweeps across the Oklahoma and Texas panhandles and neighboring areas.

events.description: World War II: Royal Marines land in Namsos, Norway, preceding a larger force which will arrive two days later.
events.html: • 1940 – World War II: Royal Marines land in Namsos, Norway, preceding a larger force which will arrive two days later.

events.description: World War II: German and Italian forces attack Tobruk, Libya.
events.html: • 1941 – World War II: German and Italian forces attack Tobruk, Libya.

events.html: • 1944 – Bombay explosion: A massive explosion in Bombay harbor kills 300 and causes economic damage valued at 20 million pounds.

events.description: Razing of Friesoythe: The 4th Canadian (Armoured) Division deliberately destroys the German town of Friesoythe on the orders of Major General Christopher Vokes.
events.html: • 1945 – Razing of Friesoythe: The 4th Canadian (Armoured) Division deliberately destroys the German town of Friesoythe on the orders of Major General Christopher Vokes.

events.description: The Soviet satellite Sputnik 2 falls from orbit after a mission duration of 162 days. This was the first spacecraft to carry a living animal, a female dog named Laika, who likely lived only a few hours.

events.html: • 1978 – Tbilisi demonstrations: Thousands of Georgians demonstrate against Soviet attempts to change the constitutional status of the Georgian language.[24]

events.html: • 1981 – STS-1: The first operational Space Shuttle, Columbia completes its first test flight.
